 ease. Knowledge is not like other assets. It can be accessed rapidly and used by thousands, often millions, of people. This makes knowledge as an asset that generated much of the wealth in the early development of most nations. And different countries and regions need different strategies to support and promote the growth of their knowledge economies. These call for nationally and regionally-based approaches, and they entail new dynamics and challenges in wealth creation, legal regulation, national and social organization and the protection of environmental and natural resources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aKnowledge, Sociology ofvCongresses. 0aKnowledge, Sociology of--Congresses. 0aPolitical sociologyvCongresses. 0aPolitical sociology--Congresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Essays.2bisacsh1 aGearty, Conor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGungwu, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIzzuddin, Mustafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKesavapany, K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoong, Lee Hsien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuah, Danny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuah, Danny, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRose, Nikolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaw, Swee-Hock, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSidel, John T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStern, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSutherland, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwee-Hock, Saw, econtributor.4ctb4ht